      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-4">Publisher-direct pricing has tripled in four years. Agency-managed pricing has moved less than half as fast.</p>
        <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-4">The supply side is charging more. The agency tier is absorbing margin to stay competitive. The squeeze is structural.</p>

        <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed font-semibold mb-4">Which raises a question:</p>
        <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">If publishers can charge 3x more for direct access and agencies can barely pass through inflation, what's the agency layer adding? Not pricing power. Not access the buyer couldn't secure themselves. The agency markup is buying convenience, not signal.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 4: How Indexing Is Destroying Paid Link Value ── -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">

      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        4. How Indexing Is Destroying Paid Link Value
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8 font-medium">
        A backlink only passes signal if the page hosting it is indexed. The moment Google deindexes a domain, every link on that domain disappears from the graph. The money spent on those links goes to zero overnight.
      </p>

      <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-5 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Google has been running indexation enforcement at scale since the <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/blog/2022/08/helpful-content-update" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">2022 Helpful Content Update</a>. Follow-up core updates have escalated it. The targets have been clear: sites that exist to host third-party content for SEO purposes.</p>
        <p>Marketplace guest post sites fit that profile exactly. Many have already been deindexed. Many more are in the queue.</p>
        <p>When your link host gets deindexed, you do not get a refund. Most marketplace services offer 6–12 month guarantees, but a replacement on another marketplace site carries the same underlying risk.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The result?</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The signal is being deindexed.</p>
        <p>Indexation is the threshold for every retrieval system AI answer engines rely on. ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, and Google's AI Overviews all cite what their retrieval layer can see. Deindexed content is invisible to both Google and the corpora AI systems retrieve from. Paid links on marketplace sites are failing this threshold systematically.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-brand bg-white rounded-r-xl pl-5 pr-4 py-4 mt-8 shadow-card">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink mb-1">Further reading</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">The full mechanism of how AI systems choose which brands to surface, and why indexed editorial coverage is the durable signal, is covered in <a href="/resources/earned-links-vs-paid-links" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">Citation Equity: Why Earned Links Beat Paid Links</a>.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 5: What The Economics Look Like Over Useful Lifespan ── -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24" style="background: #F8F7FA;">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">

      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        5. What The Economics Look Like Over Useful Lifespan
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8 font-medium">
        Same upfront cost. Different half-lives. Annualised, the comparison inverts the common assumption that earned coverage is more expensive.
      </p>

      <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-5 leading-relaxed">
        <p>A $437 paid link on a marketplace site has a one-year effective lifespan before the site is deindexed, the link drops, or the signal decays. That is $437 per useful year.</p>
        <p>A $437 earned mention on an authority publisher has a five-year useful lifespan, minimum. Established publications do not get deindexed. The mention stays in the editorial record. That is $87 per useful year.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">Same upfront cost. Five times the useful life.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The expensive option is the cheap one.</p>
        <p>The comparison holds at lower price points too. A $150 marketplace link with a one-year lifespan costs $150 per useful year. A $150 earned mention on a mid-tier trade publication, held for five years, costs $30 per useful year. Earned coverage wins on annualised economics at every tier.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── CLOSING: What The Pricing Really Measures ── -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">

      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        What The Pricing Really Measures
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-5 leading-relaxed mb-10">
        <p>Every price on this page measures the cost of a signal that used to tell search engines which brands to surface. The assumption behind buying that signal was durable ranking value in Google search.</p>
        <p>That assumption is breaking. Marketplace sites are being deindexed in waves. The links sitting on them lose their signal overnight. AI answer engines have never read those sites as authoritative — they read the pattern of your brand's name appearing across publications with accumulated editorial credibility.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">Earned editorial coverage works in the opposite direction.</p>
        <p>A placement on a recognised publication doesn't expire. It doesn't get caught in the next HCU wave. It accumulates as a brand signal across both Google and the AI systems that decide which brands to surface in answers. Every additional placement compounds the footprint those systems read.</p>
        <p>That is what a Ranking Atlas campaign earns: fixed-price editorial placements on authoritative publishers, guaranteed per campaign. The same kind of coverage that survives algorithm updates. The same signal AI systems cite. No marketplace. No retainer.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The expensive option is the cheap one.</p>
